    body: "Many senior pet owners hear about a service animal letter and wonder whether their dog or cat qualifies, whether Medicare pays for one, and what protections come with the paper. The honest answer is that the rules around service animals, emotional support animals, and Medicare coverage are often confused on the internet, and a lot of websites selling letters online are running scams. Reading this guide first will save you from sending money to a website that prints a worthless certificate.\n\nThree separate categories of animals exist under federal law in the United States. A service animal under the Americans with Disabilities Act is a dog, or in some cases a miniature horse, that has been individually trained to perform specific tasks for a person with a disability. Examples include a guide dog for the blind, a hearing dog for the deaf, or a mobility dog that helps with balance. Service animals can go into stores, restaurants, hospitals, and most public places. They do not require a letter from anyone, although owners often carry vet records for travel.\n\nThe second category is the emotional support animal, sometimes called an ESA. An ESA provides comfort to a person with a mental health condition but is not trained to perform specific tasks. ESAs have fewer legal protections than service animals. They cannot enter restaurants or stores, and as of 2021 they no longer fly free on most airlines under federal rules. The one place an ESA still has strong protection is housing, under the Fair Housing Act, where a landlord usually cannot refuse the animal or charge pet rent if a doctor or therapist writes a proper letter.\n\nThe third category is a regular pet, which is what most family dogs and cats are. Pets have no special legal status, and Medicare does not pay for any pet-related expense, including food, vet care, or pet insurance, regardless of how important the pet is to your emotional health. This guide walks you through what a real letter looks like, when you might actually need one, how to get one safely from a licensed mental health professional, how to avoid online scams, and what Medicare covers and does not cover.",
